betterquesting:10.desc:8: Defeat 50 Ender Dragons. Ender Dragons can be respawned by using four Ender Crystals on the exit portal.
Defeat 50 Withers.

Preparing for the Nether is a whole task by itself. It's dangerous, it's foreign, and it's hot. Really hot. You'll need to find ways to manage your temperature so things don't get out of control. Pack good food, bring lots of potable water, and gear up for the toughest outing so far.
Defeat 50 Ur-Ghasts
Backpacks extend your inventory. If dropped, they keep all the items inside.

To get started, we're going to need some Flint. Fast. With the No Tree Punching mod, harvesting logs with your fists isn't an option. Thankfully, we can craft 3 Gravel into a Flint. Not efficient, but it gets the job done.

With our Flint, we need to make a Flint Knife. Take the Flint to any hard surface (Stone, Cobblestone, etc) and right-click on the top of the block with the Flint in hand to get some Flint Shards. Sticks can be obtained by punching some leaves.

Now to actually get some wood. Use the Flint Knife on some tall grass to get some Plant Fibre. Three Plant Fibres can be turned into one Plant String, an early-game replacement for String. Use a Flint Shard, Plant String, and a Stick to make a Flint Hatchet. Check the JEI tab to the right for recipes
Minning early on isn't a terible idea. We can craft a Flint Pickaxe from four Flint Shards, two Sticks and a Plant String. Be wary of the dark!

betterquesting:10.name:8: I Came, I Saw, I Conquered
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Saws allow you to get more planks from logs. More is better.
Consider this an investment. Although the Flint Shovel requires precious Flint to make, it will make harvesting Gravel much easier in the early-game.

First thing we need is a Stencil Table, Part Builder, and Tool Station. This will allow us to exit the early game, and enter the world of tinkering. You only need a few Blank Patterns to complete this quest, but you may want more for later.
With an Advanced Sifting Tool, we can sift items as many times as we like, without it getting consumed in the process!
With a Basic Sifting Tool, we can easily turn Gravel into Flint at a moment's notice. It has other use cases as well, so check JEI for all the possible recipes.

You may have noticed the water droplets above the hunger bar. This is the thirst bar. Thanks to Tough as Nails, drinking is a requirement for survival. If you find yourself low on thirst, you can sneak-right-click a water source block with an empty hand to drink from it. Doing so may give you the Thirst effect - the thirst equivalent to the Hunger effect. 

You can also drink water while it's raining by looking up at the sky with an empty hand and right-clicking.

You'll need some water to bring with you. Using a Bucket isn't as nice as it sounds for bringing drinking water around.

Enter the Canteen. This item stores 3 drinks and can be refilled much like a Glass Bottle. Just right-click a water source block to fill it up!

Charcoal filters filter the dirty water you've been drinking into nice, clean water. Not only does Purified Water replenish more thirst per drink, it also won't give you the Thirst effect and is needed for crafting thirst-quenching juices.

Charcoal filters can be used on the Canteen and Water Bottles by combining them in the crafting grid.

Alternatively, Purified Water can be obtained by smelting either a Bucket of Water or a Water Bottle in the Furnace.

The Quartz Dimensional Door sends you to your own personal pocket dimension! Like an Ender Chest, but for pocket dimensions!

The personal pocket dimension has some issues. Relogging can sometimes cause you and your pocket dimension to become "unlinked", so to speak, so your Quartz Dimensional Door won't send you back to your pocket dimension. As a precaution, you can always link an Iron Dimensional Door to your pocket dimension to help you get back to it should this happen to you.

Be careful if you get a debug message once you enter your personal pocket dimension. Leaving through the way you entered isn't a good idea!

Friendly reminder: §c§lDON'T DIE

An Iron Dimensional Door can send you to a pocket dimension! A pocket dimension is a small, black void where you can do whatever you want! Blocks you place will first be placed in the black void at your feet. After that, building works as normal!

Yes, you can place another Dimensional Door inside a pocket dimension. This will take you to a new Pocket Dimension inside the current one. Don't go crazy though. Bad things happen to those who try to bend time and space to their will.

Much like the last time you were in a place like this, the rules stay the same: §c§lDON'T DIE.

You may have seen these perculiar portals around the world. They rest on Stone Bricks and form a simple doorway to another dimension. What lies beyond is dungeon full of trials. What you're after is the loot inside the dungeon. In particular, World Thread.

The dungeon is full of tricks and traps, so come prepared. Let me emphasize this.

§l§d§lCOME PREPARED!§r

The last thing you want to do in there is die. Seriously. §l§c§lYOU DON'T WANT TO DIE.§r If you die, you'll §kGo to Limbo, never to return§r. We wouldn't want that, would we?

You didn't heed the warnings. Now you'll spend an eternity here. Maybe an eternity isn't even long enough for you to reflect on what you just did.

Was it an honest mistake? Doesn't matter. We see through all. There are §4eyes§r in the dark. You shouldn't be here.

Not even death can save you. You can't even get hurt from falling.
Making tools is great and all, but it doesn't too you much good when a Skeleton can end your life so easily. Thankfully, we can also craft our own armor, albeit at a different station.

Wooden, Stone, Flint, Bone and the like are only so good for so long. We need something better. To do that, we need to cast our own material parts out of molten metals. This is where the Smeltery comes in. 

A Smeltery is a multi-block furnace of sorts. It will melt down any acceptable item into a molten version. We can pour this molten metal into a cast to be able to make tool parts.

You can construct a decently small Smeltery using the resources from this quest. Dig a 3x3 hole in the ground, and place nine of the Seared Bricks in the hole. Around the hole, use the last twelve blocks to make walls that enclose the nine Seared Bricks in the ground. One of the blocks in this wall must be the Smeltery Controller, another must be the Smeltry Drain, and a third must be a Seared Tank, filled with some Lava. Hook up the Faucet to an outside face of the Smeltery Drain, then place the Casting Table below it. With this setup, the Smeltery can melt nine different items at once. We can expand this design however you like to fit more items in at once (just check the Materials and You book). Great! Now we can make a pickaxe.

Note that when using the Smeltery, certain molten metals (like Copper and Tin) will mix together and form an alloy (in this case Bronze).

When pouring molten liquid from the Smeltery, the liquid on the bottom is always the one that gets poured out. You can click different fluids in the Smeltery GUI to set that fluid on the bottom for casting.
Now we can make some basic casts to make tools with. If you lack the Gold, Copper, or Aluminum required (Check JEI), you can also use Clay instead to make single, one-time use casts.

betterquesting:10.name:8: All your Basin are Belong to Us
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Casting Basins can be used to cast entire blocks. Check JEI for recipes.

Knightslime has some useful properties when used as armor specifically (Although it is useful elsewhere too). You can make this alloy with some Iron, Seared Stone, and Purple Slime - which you can find from the leaves found on the floating Slime Islands.
There's a lot of different materials you can use to make tools and armor. Get them all. Every. Single. One. Enough to have 1 Material Value.

Farming will be a main source of food for a while. When monsters sport big beefy health bars, hunting for food because less and less optimal. Furthermore, with the Spice of Life, eating the same food over and over again gives diminishing returns and failing to diversify yields no bonus health. Thanks to Pam's HarvestCraft, there's TONS of crops to eat. Each biome will have a Garden plant. Breaking this plant will yields lots of different mature crops, which you can craft into seeds.
The Tool Forge is an upgrade to the Tool Station, allowing you to craft a more diverse selection of weapons.
The Armor Forge is an upgrade to the Armor Station that allows you to apply modifiers to your armor. Check the Armory Addendum for recipes.

The Thermometer is a nice way to measure the surrounding temperature. The output that the Theromometer reads is the final temperature your body will adjust to before any modifications such as with armor linning or goo packs.
Heating and Cooling Coils modify the surrounding temperature immensely. Use it by placing it down and activating it with Redstone. You can even automate it by using a Season Sensor!

A Rain Collector will slowly collect rain while it is raining. Much like a Cauldron, it can store three entire buckets worth of fluid. But instead of holding plain, dirty water, the Rain Collector fills up with precious Purified Water.

Yes, seasons change thanks to Serene Seasons. In order to prepare for this, it's helpful to know what season it currently is. A Season Clock does exactly that. You can even place it in an Item Frame to get a more accurate measure of the season when you hover your croshair over it.

These are the materials you need to craft it. Now you can't open to quest book to check the season.
Season Sensors will emit a different strength of a Redstone signal depending on the current season.

Crops can only grow in their corresponding fertile season. We can help crops grow year-round using Greenhouse Glass. This lets crops grow anytime of year. Just use some Greenhouse Glass and, well, make a greenhouse!

Making a Crafting Table takes a little more work. To make one, place some logs down in the world; you can't stack logs on top of eachother for this. Then, use your Flint Hatchet and right-click the top of the log to get about two planks. It's not guarenteed. You may get less. Right-clicking on planks in a similar manner will give you about two Sticks. 

Placing a Crafting Table in your crafting grid can turn it into a Crafting Station. These tables work like Crafting Tables, but you can leave items on the table.

The Spice of Life is a mod that does two things:

1. It punishes the player for eating the same food over and over again. Eat food too much, and you'll see diminishing returns on the hunger and saturation you get back.

2. It rewards the player for diversifying. It's one thing to eat enough different foods to avoid their diminishimg returns, but it's another thing entirely to go out of you way to try all 1200+ unique food items. For every twenty §ounique§n§n§r food items you try for the first time, up to four hundred, you gain a §lpermanent§l §rextra heart.

How do you keep track of what you ate and haven't eaten? The Food Journal and the Food Book can help. The Food Journal keeps track of what you've eaten recently, to avoid diminishing returns. The Food Book shows you which foods you've eaten, and which you haven't.

The Lunch Bag can store up to three stacks of food items. Right-Click to open the bag and place items inside. Shift-Right-Click with the bag to keep the bag opened. From there, you can eat right out of the bag, and the Lunch Bag will make sure to feed you items that you haven't eaten recently.
The Lunch Box is an upgrade to the Lunch Bag. Instead of storing three different items, the Lunch Box stores six!

Some of the materials you can use for tools comes from the Nether. Don't expect this to be a cake walk. The Nether is even more dangerous than before.

Manyullyn is formed as an alloy between Cobalt and Ardite.

Nature's Compass is a neat little compass that can help you pinpoint any biome. Right-Click to select a biome. If the compass finds the specified biome, it will tell you the distance and direction you need to travel to get there. Just remember how to get back!

Handles form the base of all Spartan Weaponry. These weapons are nice, cheaper alternative to better weapons from Tinker's Construct. You can make a Handle with a Stick and some Plant String, String, or Leather even!
The Aether also opens up new possibilities for tinkering. A lot more. Here's a few of the more precious metals you can use for tinkering.
Many of the Twilight Forest items can be used for tinkering. This will open up your options even more.

Steel comes as a very useful tinkering material. You'll need to get Coal Coke with the Pyrolytic Conversion specialization for the Redstone Furnace, then place both the Coal Coke and an Iron Ingot into the Induction Smelter.
The Emerald Soul Key summons tougher bosses, but the rewards are even better.
We're still watching...

betterquesting:10.name:8: If You Can't Beat Them, Join Them!
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Summoning Staff is a powerful little staff that lets you summon powerful elementals and nasty creatures to do your bidding. You can change which mob you will summon - and their behaviour - via the Bestiary's Summoning tab. You only have so much focus; which recovers over time, and different mobs cost a different amount of focus, so keep that in mind.

betterquesting:10.name:8: If You Can't Join Them, Recruit Them!
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Using a regular Soulstone on a tamed pet binds the instance of that pet to your soul. You can summon that pet anytime, anywhere. Should the pet die, they have to spend some time respawning before you can summon them again. This summon draws from a different pool. It draws from your spirit, not your focus. You can manage your pets from the Bestiary under Pets. All pets can have pet armor equipped (Check JEI), and can have a Chest equipped to store some items. Some pets are even rideable with a Saddle!

When riding a pet, you can use their ability by pressing the corresponding key (default is "X").

First however, you need to tame a mob. Not all mobs are tameable; check the Beastiary to find out which mobs are tameable (out of the ones you've seen so far.). You'll need the corresponding treat to tame them. Be careful, they will still be aggressive until tamed!

As an aside, pets that aren't soulbound are gone forever, should they die.

Spartan Shields opens up the playing field for more durable sheild that could carry secondary effects! The base of all Sheild is the Wooden Shield, either the Crude, or Tower variant.

For these quests, you only need to craft one of the variants. You can choose which variant you prefer.
With some Cobblestone, you can upgrade the base shield into a Stone Shield. This doesn't do anything fancy, but it does last longer.
Diamond Shields last a really long time. Nothing special in terms of effects though.
The Obsidian Shield is a pretty durable shield that makes you heavier. As a result, you move quite slower with it equipped. But, you also receive less knockback as well.
A Signalum Strengthened is quite useful. Enemies that hit it are weakened for a short while. Perfect for launching a counter-attack!
The Enderium Strengthened Shield is the most durable shield available. Enemies get slowed when they make contact. Perfect for getting in quick strikes or making a quick escape!
Silver Shields are much weaker than most other shields. However, any undead mob attacking the shield gets damaged. Perfect for dealing with hordes of the undead!
The Radiant Lumium Shield is a decently durable shield that lights up enemies that hit it.
Poles form the base of many larger throwing weapons.
The Soulgazer can be used to add mobs to the Beastiary. It is also used in crafting Soulstones. The Soulgazer is not consumed in this crafting recipe.

The Lesser Equipment Forge allows you to craft weapons by combinning the parts of mobs you've slain!

You begin with a base. Placing a part that is a base type is the blue slot opens up a head slot (and sometimes a pommel slot).

Next, you add a head part is the newly coloured slot. This either opens up a blade slot, a pike slot, two axe slots, or a jewel slot.

Now, you can add your blade, axe, pike or jewel. Once you do so, you'll see your finished weapon output in the rightmost slot. You can continue customizing your weapon until you pick it up from that slot. You can not pick up your Crafted Equipment until it has an axe, pike, blade, or jewel part. For axe parts, you only need at least one axe part to complete the weapon.

You can see a preview of your weapon by hovering over the output slot once it appears there. You can see its damage and swing speed, along with any secondary effects it applies to enemies. Sometimes, you can even use your weapon as a tool.

If you want to change your Crafted Equipment at any time, place it back in the output slot at the right. This can only be done if the pieces are all level one. All the pieces will then reappear in the slots they were placed in. You can swap out parts or even dismantle the whole thing piece by piece.
The Greater Equipment Forge is an upgrade to the Lesser Equipment Forge. It readily accepts level two parts.
The Master Equipment Forge is the final upgrade to the Equipment Forge. It accepts all level parts.

As of the 'Fully Charged!' update from Lycanites, individual Equipment parts can be leveled up. You need an Equipment Infuser to do this.

If you have Crafted Equipment, you'll need to disassemble it in an Equipment Forge first. There are no consequences by doing this.

With individual equipment parts, place them into the right slot in the GUI of the Equipment Infuser. The bar below will fill up to show that part's current XP, if it has any. Then, place a charge item in the left slot. If the equipment part has a charge element that matches a charge element of the charge item, that item will be consumed and XP will be awarded to the equipment part. The maximum level an equipment part can reach is level 3. Most equipment parts can be crafted into some corresponding charge elements, allowing you to use these extra drops to power up your weapons.

The Uncrafting Table lets you turn an item back into the components used to craft it. Place something in the left slot, and the recipe will appear transparant in the middle grid. Grabbing any of these items will consume some experience, and make the rest of the items real for you to grab.

You can also craft in the Uncrafting Table.

The Hardened Upgrade Kit upgrades a Basic Machine to the Hardened level. By default, Hardened Machines will use up 30 RF/t for operations, instead of 20 RF/t - giving it a small speed boost. In addition, it unlocks an upgrade slot, where you can place an augment or specialization. Augments can improve the machine's capabilities, whereas specializations change the behaviour of the machine. Only one specialization can be installed per machine.

The Reinforced Upgrade Kit can be used on any Hardned machine to upgrade it to the Reinforced tier. Reinforced machines use up to 40 RF/t by default, and have an additional upgrade slot.

You can also craft a Reinforced Conversion Kit with the Hardened and Reinforced Upgrade Kits to instantly upgrade any Basic or Hardened machine to the Reinforced tier.

The Signalum Upgrade Kit upgrades any Reinforced machine to the Signalum Tier. Signalum machine use 50 RF/t by default, and have three upgrade slots.

You can also craft Signalum Conversion Kits with the Hardened, Reinforced and Signalum Upgrade Kits to instantly upgrade any Basic, Hardened or Reinforced machine to the Signalum tier.

The Resonant Upgrade Kit upgades any Signalum machine to the Resonant tier. Resonant machines use up to 60 RF/t by default, and have four upgrade slots.

Resonant Conversion Kits can be made with all four Upgrade Kits to convert any machine to the Resonant tier.

betterquesting:10.name:8: If You Can't Recruit Them, Enslave Them!
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Summoning Pedestal is a block that will constantly summon mobs under your command. Right-Click it to open its interface. There's a slot where you can place Redstone or Redstone Blocks to power it. Once powered, it will slowly summon the mob you selected, drawing from it's own focus, so long as it has Redstone to fuel it.

Soul Keys can be crafted with a Nether Star, Soulgazer and Diamonds. This hefty recipe gives you quite a dangerous item. Using the Soul Key on a boss or event altar will summon a terrible entity! Defeating this boss will reward the player with a Soulstone that already contains a tamed mob inside. Using it will immediately add a new mob to your list of pets.

Oh yeah, you also get a heap of other good stuff too.
The Diamond Soul Key is even better than the Emerald Soul Key, and the rewards are that much better too.

A Demonic Soulcube can be crafted using a Nether Star and some Demonstone. Demonstone can be crafted with a single Nether Wart and eight Cobblestone. This Demonic Soulcube is used in two Boss Altars to summon a powerful boss mob of your chosing. After you complete this quest, you can check the quests for the boss mobs to learn how to summon them.

Summoning Rahovart requires a Boss Altar to be summoned, but it must be built in the Nether. 

The altar consists of five towers: one central five block tower, and four outer four block towers placed diagonally away from the central tower with a one block gap between them diagonally (picture a five on a six-sided die for reference).

The central tower needs two Obsidian, the Demonic Soulcube, and two more Obsidian stacked on top of eachother in that order.

The outer towers require three Obsidian, with a Diamond Block on top.

Use a Soul Key on the Demonic Soul Cube to summon Rahovart. A massive arena will be created, so don't do this near anything valuable.

Summoning Asmodeus requires an a special Boss Altar to be summoned, however this altar can only be built in the Nether. 

This altar consists of a five block tower, surrounded by four four block towers in all the cardinal directions, with one gap in betweem them. The central tower consists of two Obsidian, the Demonic Soulcube, and two more Obsidian on top, while the outer towers require three Obsidian, with a Diamond Block stacked on top. 

Use a Soul Key on the altar to summon Asmodeus. Doing so will construct a massive arena for the battle, so do this far away from anything valuable.
Kill Rahovart 50 times.
Kill Asmodeus 50 times.
The Respawn Obelisk sets your spawn point on the fly. Just set it down and interact with it.
The Nether has a new selection of trees for you to investigate, all of which open up new tinkering possibilities. Each tree has its own unique properties. One even grows upside-down!

The Nether Chest is a storage container that behaves similarly to the Nether. Much how distances are multiplied by eight when travelling in the Nether, item stack sizes are multiplied by eight when placing items in a Nether Chest. Even items that don't stack at all (such as Beds or Totems of Undying) will stack in stacks of eight in the Nether Chest. Items like these must have the same NBT metadata in order to stack, so keep that in mind. 


Unlike an Ender Chest, the Nether Chest drops its contents when broken, similar to a regular Chest.

Just don't open one of these in the Nether. Seriously.

Slime Crystals are useful for not only tool parts. With them, you can add an Embossment modifier. Embossed tools take on the traits of the embossed item without changing any stats or traits already on the tool. It can only be done once, and it can't be changed later.

There's also a few interesting berries to find in the Nether. These berries can be found anywhere in the Nether, but are exceedingly rare. The Natura bushes themselves can be crafted if you have enough Tainted Soil, and the right Overworld berry bush.

Potash Apples drop from Darkwood leaves.

Black Apples can be found in the Nether Grasslands, an area denoted by tall Smokers, in addition to Black Bushes, Egg Plants and Nether Grass.
The Cincinnasite Forge smelts items at twice the efficiency and twice the speed!
Cincinnasite is a new material you can tinker with. You'll need to find some Cincinnasite Ore, then smelt a crafted Cincinnasite Block.

Peridot, Ruby and Sapphire are precious gemstones found underground. These gemstones can be used for tinkering. Ruby and Sapphire have identical stats, but different traits. Peridot is slightly weaker.
The Object Submission Station is used to submit quests that require a large amounts of items - larger than the player's inventory can handle. It can also be used to submit any quest.
Collect 1000 Buckets of Blood.
Build a portal frame out of Glowstone, then use a Water Bucket on it to travel to a hostile paradise. Watch your step! It's a long way down!

The Incubator allows you to grow Moas! These creatures can be ridden once fully grown with a Saddle. Place Ambrosium Torches in the lower slot of the Incubator, and a Moa Egg in the top slot. Wait a while, and soon you'll have your very own Moa.

The Enchanter takes Ambrosium as "fuel" to magically enchant items. Because of Tinkered Hegemony, The standard Aether tools are inaccessible, so their recipes in the Enchanter are moot. Most of the other recipes are used for aesthetic purposes. However, this is the only way to get Enchanted Gravitite for tinkering.

The enchanting process is very slow, but if you place some Enchanted Gravitite under the Enchanter, the process will be sped up drastically.
The Freezer is a simple Furnace-like block that takes Icestone as "fuel" to freeze certain items.

You'll find small Bronze Dungeons located in the cliffsides of the islands. Inside is a dungeon and a boss: The Slider.

Upon defeating the boss, claim this quest, then take the key to the dungeon loot which will have been uncovered. Use the key on the chest to unlock it.
High in the clouds, you'll find large Silver Dungeons. These dungeons are home of the Valkyries and their queen.
Small islands filled with Gold Oak Trees house the Gold Dungeon. Inside it is the final boss for the Aether.

The Rift Signature is a one-to-one rift creator. With the signature in hand, right-click a block to store its location. Once stored, right click elsewhere (even in another dimension) to create a rift. This rift will lead to the location stored by the signature.

You can place an Iron Dimensional Door on a rift to have the door inherit the properties of the rift (like where it takes you).
Stable Fabric is what you can use to create your own Pocket Dimensions. These are tiny dimensions similar to the ones you ventured through to get the World Thread. Except this time, it's yours!
The Gold Dimensional Door creates a new dungeon where you can get World Thread. All the rules still apply. §l§c§lDON'T DIE.§r
The Rift Remover removes a rift when you right-click one by sealing the rip in spacetime.
The Rift Stabilizer stops a rift from growing. Rifts grow logarithmically.

The Stabilized Rift Signature is a many-to-one rift creator. Much like with a regular Rift Signature, right-click a block to store its location. However, whenever you right-click again with this Stabilized Rift Signature, you'll create a new rift that is linked to the location stored. This lets you create many different Dimensional Doors that lead to the same place.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Playing With Things You Shouldn't Be
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
The Rift Blade is a simple broadsword with extra properties.

You can right-click rifts with this sword in hand to travel through the rift as if there were a portal over it.

Some say that targets attacked with this blade will be randomly teleported...

The Hunting Dimension is a solid answer to finding mobs to hunt when waiting for night in the Overworld isn't an answer. The Hunting Dimension looks exactly like the Overworld except the world has been plunged into eternal night. Only hostile mobs spawn in the Hunting Dimension.

There are consequences to doing this. All mobs in the Hunting Dimension get 30% increased attack damage and health, plus an additional 4 armor. Also, beneficial potion effects wear off twice as fast.

There are benefits to the Hunting Dimension. Mobs killed in the Hunting Dimension have a 20% chance to drop 2.5 times more experience, and a 25% chance that an additional level of Looting will be applied to their drops.

The portal frame blocks are crafted using eight logs and an Arrow in the center. The portal is activated with a Sword, Bow or Flint and Steel. Once inside the portal, sneak to warp to the Hunting Dimension. Like a Nether portal, the Hunting Dimension portal can spawn mobs. Which ones? You'll have to see.

You may notice that only mobs that spawn in Plains biomes are spawning in the Hunting Dimension. By crafting Creeping Moss, we can change the biome of a chunk in the Hunting Dimension to target specific mobs.

When in any dimension, using Creeping Moss by sneak right-clicking will store the biome ID of the biome you are currently in. Using Creeping Moss in the Hunting Dimension by right-clicking will set the biome of the chunk you're in the the biome stored in the Creeping Moss.

NOTE: Some mob spawns are actully §odimension§r specific, not biome specific. There is no way to spawn these mobs in the Hunting Dimension (e.g. Lycanites mobs that spawn in the Nether can not spawn in the Hunting Dimension).
Destroy the Slider 50 times.
Best the Valkyrie Queen 50 times
Usurp the Sun King 50 times.

Midnight also has a few metals to tinker around with. Each material in Midnight always has the Dark Traveler trait, which randomly damages all mobs around you (including players).

Caliginum is a new alloy made with Nagrilite and Tenebrum in a one to two ratio.

Midnight is a new dimension that you can explore. You can find rifts leading to Midnight on the surface, and only at night in the Overworld. You'll end up here at some point during your adventures; be it by choice or by force. Once inside, you notice that the rift that took you here vanishes. The only way out of Midnight is to find another rift (which are uncommon). These rifts once again appear only on the surface, and only when it is night in the Overworld. Don't think you can just die and leave Midnight either. Those who die in Midnight, stay in Midnight.

Everything here is dangerous, so proceed with caution.
Hungry? There's plenty to eat in Midnight, if you know where to look... Gathering all the food items in Midnight is an excellent display of mastery over the dimension.

Dark Pearls are mainly used for cosmetics. However, you will need at least one later on...

To get a Dark Pearl, you need to find the ore. Once done, minning it gives you a Geode. These can be thrown as weapons dealing a small amount of damage. If the Geode hits a tough surface (like Stone), it will shatter and drop a Dark Pearl.
There is a fair amount of plantlife that thrives in Midnight. Some are useful in tinkering, others are just peculiar

A few materials around Midnight are useful for tinkering, but don't need the Smeltery.

Ebonite is a dark ore found underground.

Archaic Shards are found inside Trenchstone boulders.
There are new trees that you can harvest in the Aether. They're even usable in tinkering

Unlike the Nether, there's only a single berry you can find here. You can however, enchant it in the Enchanter to get a better berry.

Also unlike the Nether, there's only a single apple you can find here. White Apples don't replenish hunger when eaten, but they do cure all potion effects, positive, or negative. They drop from certain Crystal Leaves.

Parachutes are key to getting around safely in the Aether. They can be crafted from Aerclouds.

The Cold Parachute is a single use item whereas the Golden Parachute has 10 uses.
Golden Amber can be harvested from Golden Oak Saplings, but only with tools that have the Gilded trait.
A Remedy Bucket can cure the effects of Poison Darts. These darts can still be used in Tinker's Dart Shooters - and they make a great addition to your arsenal.

Surround a 2x2 pool of waters wil flowers, then toss a Dark Pearl into the pool to open a portal to the Twilight Forest.

This area is for well equipped players only. Not only will you have to deal with hostile mobs almost all the time, but the difficulty increases faster here, so mobs get powered up very quickly!

Throughout the readily accessible biomes of this forest lie a few Naga Courtyards. You'll need to defeat the Naga and gather its scales in order to weaken the protective barrier around the Lich's tower.

Upon defeating the Naga, you'll gain access to the Lich's Tower. Climb up the tower, defeat the Lich, and gather its head as a reward. You'll also get a new staff to use in combat!

Once the Lich has been defeated, you're able to continue however you want. Three new areas will now be accessible.

In the Twilight Swamp, you will find an entrance to the Minoshroom's maze. Navigating this multi-floor maze won't be easy as the maze blocks can't be broken. Down at the bottom of the maze is the Minoshroom. Upon defeating it, you'll gain access to the Fiery Swamp.

In the snowy section of the Twilight Forest, there lies a large cave housing the Alpha Yeti. Don't let it pick you up.

There's no trophy for the Alpha Yeti, but grabbing some of its fur should suffice.
Within the Dark Twilight Forest, you'll find remains of a goblin stronghold. This sprawling, undergound base houses the Knight Phantoms. In order to get in, you'll need the Twilight Lich Trophy.
High glaciers lie even deeper in the snowy forest. Atop these, you can find a structure made from Aurora Blocks. Here is where the Snow Queen is.
In the Fiery Swamp, you'll find the Hydra. Expect a tough fight, as this beast has heaps of health, and deadly attacks. Defeat it, and grab the Hydra Trophy.

In the center of the Dark Forest lies a huge tower. Climbing this tower is no small feat, as it has been straight up blasted apart in some places. At the top, you'll find the Ur-Ghast. Expect an interesting fight - this thing is huge.

Deep underground in the Highlands is a massive block of Obsidian. Giant Obsidian. In order to break this, and get the loot inside, you need a pickaxe fit for the task. That pickaxe is high up in the clouds. Mine through some of the smaller Obsidian vaults to find some Magic Beans. Plant the beans on the Uberous Soil below the clouds to create a path upwards.

betterquesting:10.name:8: You Are Your Own Worst Enemy
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Climb the beanstalk (this sounds familiar) to reach the cloud high in the sky. Up there you'll find... yourself? But huge?

You'll need to defeat your giant counterpart and grab a Giant's Pickaxe. This pickaxe can be used on the Obsidian Vault to get to the Lamp of Cinders. This lamp will let you destory those pesky thorns!

You can get through the Thornlands to reach the Final Plateau. A massive castle awaits for you to explore. The final challenge of the Twilight Forest lies ahead. All you need to do is...

Wait.

Yes, wait.

The finale of this chapter isn't finished. The amazing people who made mod haven't finished it. It's been an awesome journey thus far. If you manage to get to the top of the castle, where the final boss should be, you can find their Discord channel, where they'll be posting information related to the development of this mod. Even when the final castle is finished, they still have more content in their design documents waiting to be implemented!

To complete this quest, click the checkbox.

Vitalium is a new alloy you can make with Molten Life Force and Blood. Molten Life Force can be obatined from Heart Containers, Heart Crystal Shards, and Heart Crystal Dust. Check JEI for the alloying recipe.
Defeat 50 Nagas

betterquesting:10.name:8: You Can't Kill What's Already Dead
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Kill the Twilight Lich 50 times
Defeat the Minoshroom 50 times.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Now You See it, Now it's Dead
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Kill the Knight Phantom 50 times.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Could You Possibly Do That, Hercules?
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Kill the Hydra 50 times.
Defeat the Alpha Yeti 50 times.
Defeat the Snow Queen 50 times.
Defeat 50 Sirens

The Charm of Keeping can help you keep parts of your inventory on death.

A level one charm will keep your curently selected item.

A level two charm will keep your entire hotbar.

A level three charm keeps your entire inventory.
The Charm of Life protects you similar to a Totem of Undying, except it can stack and acts as a Bauble.
The Questing Ram can be found in the Questing Grove. To complete its quest, you must give it every colour of Wool. You will then get its head as a reward.
There's a whole new selection of trees in the Twilight Forest. These trees have no special properties, but they sure do look neat.

The Twilight Forest has four saplings you can find that can create trees with special powers. The power of the tree comes from the core, found in the trunk. This core can not be harvested. Instead, it drops a respective log. The power of the tree can be turned on or off by right-clicking the core.

A Timewood tree has the effect of speeding up crop growth and nearby machines.

A Transformation tree has the effect of changing the nearby area in the enchanted forest biome from the Twilight Forest

A Miner's tree has the effect of pulling valuable ores out of the ground and to the surface.

A Sorting tree sorts nearby chests by ID numbers.
The Mazebreaker Pickaxe is a difficult to find pickaxe that requires a Maze Map to find a secret room. The Maze Breaker can break parts of the maze without worrying about losing extra durability.

The Machine Frame is the basis for all machines. There many more machines than the ones listed through these quests. The ones in these quests happen to be the most impactful. Check JEI for all the uses of the Machine Frame.

The Device Frame is the basis for all devices. Devices are blocks that don't need a source of power to function.

These aren't all the possible devices. Check JEI for a complete list.

The Redstone Furnace ought to be the first machine you make. You can smelt items using RF instead of fuel. The more RF/t you can provide it, the faster it will smelt items.

All machines can be configured to enable auto input and auto output. If auto input is enabled, the machine will pull corresponding input items from inventories adjacent to the appropriately configured sides and place the input slots. If auto output is enabled, the machine will eject the contents of its output slot to the corresponding side if it has an inventory that can accept the output item. This can even be another machine!
The Trivection Chamber specialization increases the Redstone Furnace's output for food based items. However, the Redstone Furnace will only accept food items, and will not smelt any other item.
The Flux Anodizers specialization increases the Redstone Furnace's output from ores. However, the Redstone Furnace will only accept ores, are will not smelt any other items.
The Pulverizer smashes items into other items using RF. Typically, this process can't be undone.
The Induction Smelter smelts two items together using RF. This can be used to make alloys without having to go through the Smeltery, or increase ore outputs. This is the primary way to make Steel.
The Aqueous Accumulator collects water, and only water, from adjacent water sources. It does not remove the water source in the process.
The Arboreal Extractor extracts Resin out of a tree behind it. Not all trees are compatible.
The Aquatic Entangler catches fish for you. You can provide Aqua-Chow to speed it up. It must be placed ina body of water to function.
The Thermal Mediator speeds up cardinally adjacent machines by 20% if supplied with Water, or 40% if supplied with Gelid Cryotheum
The Gear Cast is currently the only way you can make gears from tougher materials.
The Compactor can press metals into plates and press various other items using RF. Check JEI.
The Phytogenic Insulator can artificially grow plant life using RF.
The Sawmill shreds wooden items into planks, and shreds other items into some component parts using RF.
The Magma Crucible can melt items into various liquids using RF.
The Nether Furnace is a new Furnace made of Netherrack. It smelts things with twice the efficiency, effectively doubling your fuel.
The Fractioning Still can distill liquids into a more refined version using RF.
The Hypoinfuser can inject any potion stored inside it into any mob, even yourself!

The Energy Cell can store lots of RF. Configure which sides will intake RF and which will output RF. Like machines, you can use Upgrade Kits on the Enegy Cell to increase the amount of RF it can store along with how much RF it can intake and output.
The Steam Dynamo converts Water into Steam to produce RF. It does so by burning most types of fuels that a Furnace can take.
The Magmatic Dynamo takes certain hot fluids and converts them into RF.
The Compression Dynamo converts liquid fuel into RF. It needs to be supplied with coolant to run.
The Reactant Dynamo takes a solid reactant and a fluid to create a reaction that will produce RF.
The Enervation Dynamo converts the RF stored in objects into RF output.
The Numismatic Dynamo converts... currency into power? Don't question it.

Viaducts transport players from one point to another. The speed the players travel depends on the variant used. Each variant has pros and cons.

Whoosh.
Itemducts transfer items from one inventory to another. The items will always take the shortest path. Path lengths can be changed by using Dense or Vacuum variants.

Fluiducts can transport fluids from one machine to another. Just get a machine (or device) to output a fluid into a fluiduct and connect the Fluiduct to another machine (or Fluiduct) to transport the fluid.
Super Laminar Fluiducts can instantly transport fluids through networks of other Super Laminar Fluiducts.

Fluxducts can transport RF. The amount of RF a Fluxduct can transfer depends on the type of Fluxduct. A Leadstone Fluxduct will transfer up to 1000 RF/t, but this will be distributed over all connections in the network.
Cryo-Stabilized Fluxducts have and infinite transfer rate of RF. However, they have no residual capacitence, so each Cryo-Stabilized Fluxduct will not store any RF of its own.
Satchels act as additional inventory space. Right-click with one in hand to open it. Their size can be upgraded.
A Strongbox is simply a Chest that can store items. It starts off with a small inventory, but this can be upgraded. In addition, Strongboxes retain their items when broken.
The Crecent Hammer lets you rotate and dismantle machines. It also lets you tweak how your ducts interact with neighboring ducts and machines.

The Ore Magnet attracts ores in a 32 block radius, towards the player. It searches in the direction the player is facing, and will find any non-Coal ore and bring some or all of it towards you. It can only be found in Hollow Hills, and has 12 durability, but can be enchanted with Unbreaking and Mending.
The Tectonic Initiator Specialization in the Pulverizer will allow the Pulverizer to receive an increased yield from ores. However, it must be supplied with Tectonic Petrotheum
The Pyro-Concentrator allows the Induction Smelter can receive and increased output from ores. However, it must be supplied with Blazing Pyrotheum.
Coal Coke can be produced using the Pyrolytic Conversion specialization in the Redstone Furnace. This is a required ingredient to produce Steel.
The Numismatic Press allows the Compactor to produce Coins instead of Plates. These coins are used in the Numismatic Dynamo.
The Gearworking Die can compress 4 of a material into their respective gear. It will no longer make Plates.
The Tome of Knowledge can store experience for you. You can convert this experience into Essence of Knowledge which can used in some machines.

Thermal Cultivation gives a whole new way to grow crops! Crops will need to be in their fertile season or placed in a greenhouse to grow. Not with Thermal Cultivation's Watering Can! This bad boy can store up to four buckets of water at a time and can irrigate farmland in a 3x3 area centered on you. Also, crops in this area also get a bonus to their growth speed so long as you water them! 

Like most Thermal items, this Watering Can is upgradable, able to hold a whopping sixty buckets of water fully upgraded, and able to irrigate a massive 11x11 area (this also applies to the bonus growth too)! By default, you can press "V" to change the area affected by the Watering Can. This size must be at least 3x3. The maximum area depends on the tier of Watering Can, with each higher tier Watering Can able to use all the smaller areas below it:

Basic: 3x3
Hardened: 5x5
Reinforced: 7x7
Signalum: 9x9
Resonant: 11x11
The Presser is a very important block to have. It can press blocks into two items. What's more, it can press vanilla and HarvestCraft logs into extremely valuable Paper!

The Grinder can grind up meat into ground meat, which is usable in some recipes.

It can also grind up items into bait, which can be used in traps to catch food!
What's the buzz about bees? Well, bees can help you get a collection of useful resources!
The Apiary can be used to get Honey Combs, Wax Combs and Bee Grub from a Queen Bee. These items can be used for food!
The Shipping Bin lets you sell unwanted crops for Emeralds!
The Market lets you trade Emeralds for crops without needing a Village!

Traps let you use ground bait to catch food!

As you might expect, the Water Trap must be placed in water to function. The Water Trap must be touching at least five other water source blocks to function (this includes diagonally). Then, place the Fish Trap Bait into the left slot. You'll know the trap is working if it immediately consumes a bait.

The Ground Trap must be placed in the ground with all four sides touching Grass Blocks, and the top being exposed to the sky. Then, place a bait of choice in the left slot. The type of bait determines what items you'll get, but no matter what, you always have a chance of getting Leather, Feathers, Eggs, Bones and Raw Chicken, no matter what bait you use. You'll know the trap is working if it immediately consumes a bait.

Cooking For Blockheads aims to simplify the cooking process for everyone. So, how do you get a recipe book anyway? Easy, just burn it.

Seriously.

Just smelt a Book. Just. DO IT.

Now that we have all these cooking tools, it's time to build a place to use them! A Kitchen is a multiblook structure that starts with the Cooking Table. The Cooking Table acts like Cooking For Blockheads II, but in block form.

But what's a kitchen without kitchen flooring? Kitchen Floor allows you to connect Kitchen Counters and Kitchen Cabinets to your Cooking Table, you you can use the ingredients in these cupboards to cook without having to acutally go fetch them! Just place the storage units and Cooking Table on a single, connected section of Kitchen Floor.

Basically just build a kitchen.
The #NoFilter Edition of the Cooking For Blockheads Cookbook shows ALL the food recipes!
Cooking For Blockheads II will actually craft the food item for you, instead of showing you just the recipe. You still have to have the items in your inventory to craft it.

Refrigerators are basically additional storage units. You can place two on top of eachother to get a larger fridge.

Refridgerators are also dyeable.

Ovens can cook up to nine different food items at once. You can also store certain cooking tools on it as well. It does use slightly more fuel per operation, but since a single operation cooks nine items, you're saving fuel in the long run, should you cook multiple items at once.
A Milk Jar can hold milk to be used in recipes.

There's a few more blocks you can put in your kitchen to make it a little nicer.

The Fruit Basket can hold different fruits to be used in recipes.

The Spice Rack can hold different ingredients. Like spices.

The Tool Rack can hold different tools used in cooking. It can only hold two at a time.

The Toaster can turn Bread into Toast. Magic.

The Preservation Chamber is an upgrade for the Refrigerator that prevents stored food items from running out in crafting recipes.

It works by never letting the count of the item drop below 1. This does mean that you will not be able to craft food with that item

So you place a Milk Jar, then you lure a Cow on top of it, and then drop an Anvil on it. Presto! Cow in a Jar!

A Cow in a Jar will slowly produce milk for recipes.
The Heating Unit is an upgrade for the Oven that allows you to cook items in the Oven with energy (RF). The stored energy meter only updates when items are cooking.
The Ice Unit is an upgrade to the Refrigerator that gives snow and ice to recipes that use it.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Everything Now Includes the Kitchen Sink
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Kitchen Sink provides water to recipes that need it. In fact, it provides an infinite amount of water to anything; for example, a Watering Can.
You can't just make every food item with your bare hands! You'll need tools for it. Thankfully, these tools are reusable.
The Cutting Board can be used much like a tool in recipes. However, it can also be placed in the world, and works in a multiblock Kitchen.

Collect every Music Disc, and craft a Jukebox to play them all!

Standard Music Discs are collected the same way you expect. Have a Skeleton kill a Creeper.

Charm's Menu, Creative, Overworld and Nether Music discs are obtained similarly. Have a Skeleton kill a Zombie and it will randomly drop one of these discs.

In addition, you can pour some molten Nether Quartz on an Aether disc to turn it into a Nether Music Disc. Check JEI to see which discs turn into which.

Aether's Music Discs can be obtained through dungeon loot, or by using the Enchanter or Freezer.

Then all you need is a Jukebox.

What's that you say? There's one more record? The creepy sounds of Limbo?

...

I have no idea what you're talking about.
Complete this quest to update the quest book and reward items

Miasma is the Midnight version of Lava. What's more, it lasts longer when used in the Smeltery!

Miasma Surface can be melted into Miasma.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Material at the End of the Game
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Stygium is a very quirky material that changes its behaviour when its health (durability) is high or low, or when the wielder is at full health. The particular weapon stats may be off-putting to some, but keep in mind you can always emboss a material's traits onto your weapon.

Stygium is made by alloying Stygian Acid, Dragon's Breath, and Vitalium. Stygian Acid is found on the outer End islands. Check JEI for the exact alloying ratios.
Collect 1,440 Buckets of Molten Pigiron. This is exactly 1,000 ingots of Pigiron.
Collect 1,440 Buckets of Molten Fire Dragonsteel and Molten Ice Dragonsteel. This is exactly 1,000 ingots of both metals.

The Skill Book is an item that lets you turn levels into skill points to invest in unique skills from doubling ores to doing more damage.

When you use the book for the first time, you'll need to select a class. This gives you bonus skill points in certain trees along with a starting set of skills. It also determines your specialization. You can have one of three specializations: Combat, Crafting, and Minning. Combat gives you bonus XP when fighting mobs, Crafting gives you XP for crafting items, and Minning gives you bonus XP when minning ores.

To actually get skill points, use the Skill Book while sneaking. This will convert five levels into a skill point.
The Book of Specialization Change lets you change your specialization. You need 30 levels to do this.
Slay 50 Fire Dragons. The dragon's age doesn't matter for this quest.
Slay 50 Ice Dragons. The dragon's age doesn't matter for this quest
Kill 50 Hunters
Defeat 50 Myrmex Queens. They can be either Jungle or Desert variants.
Defeat 50 Basalz
Defeat 50 Blaze

Dark Sticks can be made from any Midnight planks. These Dark Sticks can be used with Bogshroom Powder, Nightshroom Powder, Dewshroom Powder or Viridshroom Powder to make a certain type of Sporch. Sporches act just like Torches but since these aren't actually Torches, mobs that target and destroy Torch variants won't destroy Sporches!
Defeat 50 Blizz
Defeat 50 Blitz

Stone Rods can be made with any variant of Cobblestone. Using Coal or Charcoal, you can craft Stone Torches. These Stone Torches are stronger than regular torches, preventing Zombies from destorying them. Other mobs like Kobolds, can still pick up and run off with them howvever, so keep that in mind.

Stone Torches also have the added benefit of not setting flammable blocks alight when dropped as an item.
A Feral Flame Lantern Lights up a 64 block radius around it. It's not perfect, so there may be a few mob spawns, but it should reduce spawns a lot.

The Mega Torch is the ultimate torch. This massive torch seems like a glorified torch at first, but this block prevent natural hostile mob spawns in a 64 block radius around it!

For a different flavour, try the Dread Lamp. This block prevents natural passive mob spawns in a 64 block radius around it. Both blocks are very useful.

An Undead Soulcube can be crafted with a Nether Star and Shadowstone. Shadowstone can be crafted with a single Obsidian and eight Cobblestone. This Undead Soulcube is used in a Boss Altar to summon a powerful boss mob! The next quest will explain how to summon it.

Amalgalich is a powerful boss mob that can only be summoned with a Boss Altar. This altar needs to be built in the Overworld.

The altar consists of five towers: one central five block tower, and four outer four block towers placed diagonally away from the central tower with a one block gap between them diagonally (picture a five on a six-sided die for reference).

The central tower needs two Obsidian, the Undead Soulcube, and two more Obsidian stacked on top of eachother in that order.

The outer towers require three Obsidian, with a Diamond Block on top.

Using a Soulkey on the Undead Soulcube will summon Amalgalich! A massive arena will be constructed for the fight, so build this altar far, far away from anything valuable.
Kill Amalgalich 50 times.

The Etheric Gem allows you to bound your pets to your soul. to do so, just show your pet some love and punch them with the gem in hand (and do the same thing to unbind a pet). Once a pet is bound, and should it die, this pet will respawn next to the player when the player next sleeps in a bed. This can cause the pet to spawn in a wall if you're not careful.

The gem can be used repeatedly. You only need to craft it once, and the gem can bind any number of pets at a given time.

The Tool Belt acts as a nice way to carry lots of different tools around without them clogging up your hotbar. To equip the Tool Belt, you need to open its special inventory slot (default 'V'). 

Once the Tool Belt is placed in this slot, press 'R' (default) while either holding a tool, or holding nothing to bring up a radial menu. If holding a tool, you can hover your mouse over an empty slot in that radial menu to place a tool you're holding inside. If you hover over another tool in this manner, you'll swap tools. If holding nothing, you can pull a tool out of the belt in the same manner. It's quite intuitive.

The Tool Belt is Baubles-aware so it can be placed in the belt slot. Keep in mind that the tool belt will be treated as a Bauble in this case. To guarentee the belt doesn't drop on death, place it in the special Tool Belt slot.

By default, the Tool Belt only holds 2 items. By crafting a Belt Pouch, you can place both the Tool Belt and the Belt Pouch in an Anvil to combine them together an unlock an additional slot in your belt. This costs more experience each time you do it.

Crafting Lycanites Weapons can be very useful. They may not output as much damage as Tinker's weapons, especially later on, but they have useful traits that Tinker tools don't have (at least, they don't get these traits very easily).

Certain Lycanites weapons double as a tool, allowing you to harvest large swaths of blocks of a particular type.

All Lycanites weapons are unbreakable, giving you a last resort in battle should your Tinker's weapon break.

Certain level 3 equipment parts have a chance to summon a minion to help in battle.

Finally, each equipment part that came from a mob will always apply some effect on the target. Combining these effects in strategic ways can be surprisingly effective!

For this quest, you just need to craft any equipment.
The Cobalt Shield is like the Obsidian Shield, except it grants full knockback immunity when held or equiped as a bauble!
The Bountiful Bauble Obsidian Shield grants the same perks as the Cobalt Shield, but also grants partial fire resistance as well

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Shield to End All Shields
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Ankh Shield grants partial fire resistance, immunity to most negative status effects while also granting complete knockback immunity

Spectral Silt is used for crafting various Baubles. It can be found in a variety of dungeon chests, from standard dungeons, to desert temples, and a whole lot more.

It can additionally be crafted from a Disintegration Tablet. Crafting this tablet with any Bauble from Bountiful Baubles, will reward a single Spectral Silt.

The quests that become available after completing this one only showcase a few of the possible Baubles you can craft from Spectral Silt. Check JEI for a comprehensive list.

Glowing Ingots are used for crafting much more powerful Baubles. However, these ingots are very expensive.

The quests that become available after completing this one list a few of the possible uses for Glowing Ingots. Check JEI for a complete list.
The Reforger can reroll the random qualities you get on Baubles, at the cost of some XP. All qualities provide positive effects
The Ankh Charm grants immunity to blindness, nausea, weakness, hunger, slowness, minning fatigue, levitation, poison and wither.

betterquesting:10.name:8: All You Need Now is Liquid Cooling
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Ring of Overclocking protects you from slowness. It has a 3% chance of dropping from Strays. It can also be crafted with a handful of resources.
The Ring of Free Action lets grants you immunity to slowness and levitation, along with granting free movement through cobwebs. The Shulker Heart has a 10% chance of dropping from Shulkers.

The Black Dragon Scale protects the user from wither. You'll either need to find a Cracked Black Dragon Scale, or craft one using an Ender Dragon Scale (which drops from the Ender Dragon). Then, using some Spectral Silt, an Ender Dragon Scale, and a Nether Star, you can repair this scale into a fully functioning Black Dragon Scale.
The Forbbiden Fruit is a Bauble that protects you from hunger and nausea. It has a 2.5% chance of dropping from Husks. You can also craft it from a Black Apple and a White Apple
Vitamins protect the user from minning fatigue and weakness. They drop from Elder Guardians. They can also be crafted with some Electrum, Vitalium and Spectrial Silt.
The Mixed Colour Dragon Scale protects the user from wither and poison. The Bezoar has a 5% chance of dropping from Cave Spiders.

The Lucky Horseshoe prevents fall damage.




I don't know why the horse needed this either.
The Balloon lets you jump higher, and sustain less fall damage. It doesn't completely negate it though.
The Glowing Gewm is a crafting component used for crafting powerful baubles. It isn't cheap either
The Stone of Negative Gravity allows you to slowly float in place. When held, it makes you ascend uncontrollably.
The Ring of Enchanted Eyes grants its wearer Night Vision
The Polarized Stone lets you pull or repell nearby items. You can also use it to stop arrows dead in their tracks.
The Stone of the Sea lets you freely swim underwater, and never run out of air.

The Ring of the Dwarves will transform you into a dwarf. Thiw will reduce your damage and your size, but grant you XP when minning Stone, and yeild higher ore returns on ores you mine. You can also craft it into a Dwarf Stout to premanately remain transformed.

The Dragon's Eye is a powerful Bauble that grants Fire Resistance, and the ability to search for any ore or loot chest. Sneaking while searching for a block will cause the targeted blocks to play sounds of the Ender Dragon when you're close.

You can also toggle permanent Night Vision at any time with this Bauble.

The Ring of the Fairies will transform you into a fairy when worn. This will reduce your damage, your health, your size and your jump height, but let you fly at will, sneak into very small areas, and climb certain blocks. You can turn the Fairy Ring into Fairy Dew, a one time consumable item to permanently remain transformed.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Defying the Laws of the Universe
betterquesting:10.desc:8: The Stone of Greater Intertia grants immunity to fall damage, knockback, and also grants a massive speed boost.

The Ender Queen's Crown turns you into a queen in the eyes of the Endermen. They will follow you around and defend you at any cost.

Now taking after the Endermen, you should probably avoid water. Might hurt...

What better way to become stronger than directly increasing your stats?

Scaling Health presents a way to increase your health by crafting Heart Containers. Keep in mind, Heart Crystal Shards have many uses, check JEI and make sure you prioritize!

Scaling Feast presents a way to increase your hunger by crafting Hearty Shanks. The recipe isn't cheap though, but its well worth it, since starvation leads to instant death, and hunger itself decreases a little faster than normal.
Sinisteel is a hard to get material that can inflict increasing levels of Wither to a foe when used in a tool.
Slay each Zombie variant 50 times.
Slay each Skeleton variant 50 times.
Slay each Spider variant 50 times
Slay the Nether Lord 50 times.
Slay 50 Elder Mages

Netherium is a material you can get by defeating the Nether Lord. This powerful material can only be used for armor, but packs some of the highest defense in the game. You can summon the Nether Lord like you would summon an Iron Golem, but using a Cursed Pumpkin and 4 Obsidian.
§0§WWhen you need to flex how awesome you are.
A brand new adventure awaits! Wait a second, things don't seem to be like last time.
Basically how you get anything done this time around.
ESCAPE.
Fearsome mobs that will spawn EVERYWHERE you go! Time to use that to your advantage!
They do say that defense is the best offense! That, and Boomerangs. What do you mean no one's said that before...?
The Nether is a super dangerous place, but the rewards are also just as sweet. Ready to get heated?
To the heavens! Time to harness divine power to smite your enemies! Or y'know, you could just ride a Moa.
The last thing you want is to end up in here unprepared. Sleep with the lights on!
A mystical forest filled to the brim with bugs, the undead, the eldritch and more!
Masterful machines make most missions manageable!
Now that you know how to survive, it's time to thrive!
Should you really be messing with this stuff?
A dimension just for hunting mobs!
Baubles are useful items that can give insanely good effects, when paired together correctly.
